This is the crucial step. In real physics, this is where conservation and dissipation constraints usually kill the fantasy. In simulation, though, you can study what kinds of rectification rules create stable directional behavior.

5. Feed-forward reinforcement
A small portion of the captured output is used to tune the resonator forward:

* shift phase
* adjust damping
* tighten coherence
* bias toward the next favorable tangent

So the engine becomes a prediction-assisted surfer, not just a passive absorber.

Mathematical skeleton

A simple starting point is:

x'' + \gamma x' + \omega^2 x + \beta x^3 = \eta(t) + u(t)

Where:

* x is system displacement
* \gamma is damping
* \omega is natural frequency
* \beta x^3 gives nonlinear behavior
* \eta(t) is stochastic background input
* u(t) is the control/feed-forward term

Then define an extraction/storage variable:

E_{store}' = G(x, x', \phi, C) - L(E_{store})

Where G is a gating function that only activates when:

* phase \phi is favorable
* coherence C exceeds threshold
* tangent sign matches target direction

A simple gating rule might be:

G =
\begin{cases}
\alpha x'^2 & \text{if } x' \cdot \hat{t} > 0 \text{ and } C > C_{min} \\
0 & \text{otherwise}
\end{cases}

That means:

* only harvest when motion is aligned with a chosen tangent direction
* ignore or damp the rest

Then feed-forward control:

u(t+\Delta t) = k_1 \hat{\phi}(t) + k_2 \hat{C}(t) - k_3 x(t)

This nudges the oscillator into future favorable phase regimes.

